Lateinamerika im Kampf gegen das Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not meet this crisis decisively, it could become the tragically worst episode in Latin American history.
To date, political responses in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and made the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, unfortunately, downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders chose a populist and divisive policy amidst the tragedy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
The politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing idle infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
Additionally, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other vital resources and support additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in contrast to US President Donald Trump, who made an irresponsible decision to freeze about $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatments and vaccines – in order to finally bring an end to the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has Latin American domestic production been interrupted, but the countries there also suffer from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to absent tourism, fewer foreign remittances, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contraction spiral together with a collapse in demand.
To prevent this, bold measures are needed to protect household incomes.
This means transfers to those affected by the crisis, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief for businesses is also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay wages and benefits protect both them and their employees during the crisis. They are crucial for a swift economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the wave of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at that point, the payment system—and with it the entire economy—is at risk.
Viele Unternehmen, insbesondere die kleinen und mittleren, werden während der Krise erhebliche Einkommensverluste erleiden.
Ohne Unterstützung wird der Mangel an Liquidität bald zu einem Solvenzproblem.
Steuerstundungen, Zahlungsaufschub und subventionierte Kredite werden nicht reichen.
Diese Notlage erfordert nicht nur beispiellose Kreditgarantien durch die Regierungen, um zu gewährleisten, dass die Banken weiterhin Geld verleihen, sondern auch temporäre Regulierungsänderungen, um die Kreditexpansion zu fördern.
Auch gut kapitalisierte und verwaltete staatliche Banken können dabei eine führende Rolle übernehmen.
In general, the measures may vary from country to country, but in any case, extraordinary budget resources will likely be necessary to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening health risks.
The problem is that fiscal space in Latin America today is even tighter than after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, budget adjustments in areas of lesser priority must be made.
The risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness can be reduced through government promises to correct higher budget deficits within an appropriate time frame.
<s>Allerdings wird – insbesonders für die kleinen und weniger entwickelten lateinamerikanischen Länder – dringend eine externe Unterstützung der Haushalte und Zahlungsbilanzen benötigt.
<s>Gehen sowohl Privatunternehmen als auch Staaten höhere Defizite ein, werden sich wahrscheinlich auch die Leistungsbilanzen der Länder verschlechtern.
<s>Die jüngsten Kapitalabflüsse aus den Schwellenländern – eine der größten Umkehrungen in der modernen Geschichte der Finanzmärkte – verstärken das Problem noch.
<s>Die daraus resultierenden Währungsabwertungen können einen destabilisierenden Einfluss haben.
<s>In vielen Volkswirtschaften der Region wird der einzige Weg zur Bewältigung dieser sich gegenseitig verstärkenden Schocks darin bestehen, viel mehr externe Unterstützung zu erhalten.
<s>Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
It needs to address the short-term currency and budgetary needs of the countries and continue to support their economies during this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
For this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a new edition of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights, which should amount to one billion SDRs.
While SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the oversight of the Fund.
Additionally, the IWF could create the necessary capacity by doubling the volume of New Credit Facilities immediately.
And finally, given that traditional IWF credit programs are not being approved in time, the Fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with rapid disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or establish new pandemic credit facilities.
Central banks that issue reserve currencies could help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IWF or the International Monetary Fund, which can further extend liquidity to central banks.
At home, central banks must use all available instruments and, if necessary, create new ones to provide financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
Finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) like the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursements in the region and tap into high-liquid global capital markets to provide additional fiscal support.
<s>Under exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented with a debt haircut.
<s>The MDBs should also provide guidelines to the countries regarding the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of the COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – especially for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
<s>Time plays a decisive role here.
<s>This challenge posed by the pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
<s>The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Gegenseitiges Vertrauen, Transparenz und Vernunft bleiben in diesen unsicheren Zeiten die besten Leitlinien – und nicht Populismus oder Demagogie.
Die Krise darf nicht als Entschuldigung dafür dienen, unsere hart erarbeiteten Bürgerrechte zu schwächen.
Statt dessen kann sie als Gelegenheit dienen, die Demokratie in Lateinamerika zu stärken und zu zeigen, was diese den Bürgern bieten kann.
